      "kind": "UNIFYING_DISCOVERY",
      "summary": "ChannelMixer with a diagonal 1.5x matrix produces BIT-IDENTICAL FCP output to PAEBrightness x1.5: (200,50,50)->[255,154,151] and (50,200,50)->[179,255,161] match Brightness exactly. This EXPERIMENTALLY CONFIRMS the binary decode (Brightness = diagonal HGColorMatrix) AND unifies two 'separate' divergences into ONE mechanism.",
      "mechanism": "HGColorMatrix, when a channel's output exceeds 1.0 (amount>1 / amplifying matrix), applies a cross-channel CLAMP/rolloff in its working space that LIFTS the non-clipped channels far beyond the linear result (low 50->154 when high 200 clips). Non-amplifying matrices (all outputs <=1) are VERIFIED exact in sRGB (transfer.PAEChannelMixer). So the divergence is EXACTLY the HGColorMatrix over-1.0 clamp behavior, shared by ALL HGColorMatrix filters (Brightness, ChannelMixer, and likely the matrix stage of others).",
      "models_refuted": "Not linear-space multiply ([239,62,62]), not Reinhard/Reinhard-extended, not YCbCr scale. The low-channel lift (50->154, ~3x) is larger than any standard highlight rolloff \u2014 needs the HGColorMatrix render disasm (clamp/ExtendedLinearSRGB readback stage) read from the binary.",
      "value": "Collapses Brightness + ChannelMixer(clip) into a SINGLE decodable HGColorMatrix-clamp mechanism. Decoding that one clamp fixes both (and any other HGColorMatrix filter). Gate-blocked (oracle_truth=gui) but structurally unified."
    }
